les":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Burton, Buckingham, England":"Burton, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"abt1336–":"circa 1336–Overleden","1336–Male":"1336–Overleden","1340–Female":"1340–Overleden","1372–Male":"1372–Overleden","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1316–Female":"1316–Overleden","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1455":"1455","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","abt1336":"circa 1336","1340":"1340","abt 1372":"circa 1372","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","Dyffryn Golach, Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Burton, Buckingham, England":"Burton, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"abt1336–":"about 1336–Deceased","1336–Male":"1336–Deceased","1340–Female":"1340–Deceased","1372–Male":"1372–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1316–Female":"1316–Deceased","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1455":"1455","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","abt1336":"about 1336","1340":"1340","abt 1372":"about 1372","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","Dyffryn Golach, Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Burton, Buckingham, England":"Burton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Graunt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish, English, and especially Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>graund</i>, <i>graunt</i> ‘tall, large’ (Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i>, from Latin <i>grandis</i>), given either to a person of remarkable size, or else in a relative way to distinguish two bearers of the same personal name, often representatives of different generations within the same family.","English: from the rare Middle English (and Old English) personal name <i>Grante</i> or <i>Grente</i>.","Irish: in Ireland this is usually the Norman Scottish name (see 1 above), but it was also adopted for Irish <b>Mag Raighne</b>, see   Graney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Graney","meanings":["Irish (Galway, Cork, and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Raighne</b> ‘son of <i>Raighne</i>’, a pet form of <i>Raghnall</i>. It has sometimes been changed to   Grant  . See also   Rainey  .","Possibly an altered form of Swiss German <b>Gräni</b>, unexplained."]},{"name":"Grand","meanings":["French: nickname from Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i> ‘tall, large’, from Latin <i>grandis</i>. See also   Grant   1 and 4, compare   Degrand   and   Legrand  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived in a gravelly area, from Middle Low German <i>grand</i> ‘coarse gravel’.","German: nickname from a southern word of uncertain origin meaning ‘frustration, anger, ire’."]},{"name":"Grande","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Rocco, Domenic, Mario, Antonio, Santo, Orlando, Americo, Carmine, Gennaro, Luigi, Pasquale, Saverio, Alberico.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Alicia, Ricardo, Jorge, Juan, Raul, Angel, Atilio.","Italian, Spanish, and Portuguese: nickname for someone of large stature, in either a literal or figurative sense, from <i>grande</i> ‘tall, large’.","German: habitational name from Grande in Holstein or Grand in Bavaria."]},{"name":"General","meanings":["African American: from the English vocabulary word <i>general</i>, possibly adopted as a surname in honor of a certain general of the US army, most probably Ulysses S. Grant (see   Grant  , compare   President  ). Compare also 3 below.","German: nickname for a mercenary (employed in royal services).","Hispanic (mainly Philippines): nickname from Spanish <i>general</i> ‘general’ (military officer)."]}]},{"name":"Holl","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Oliver  , frequent in the Middle Ages and occasionally revived in modern times. The initial consonant seems to derive from the misdivision of a vocative phrase;  compare  Ned   and   Nan ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Bottom","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): topographic name for someone who lived in a dell, hollow, or valley floor, from Middle English <i>bot(h)me</i>, Old English <i>botm</i> ‘valley bottom’. Compare   Botham  .","Americanized form (mistranslation into English) of French   Lafond  , in which Old French <i>la fond</i> ‘the fountain’ is confused with modern French <i>le fond</i> ‘the bottom’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bottoms","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire): variant of   Bottom  , with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Bottum","meanings":["English: variant of   Bottom  ."]},{"name":"Bitton","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Meyer, Yoram, Aharon, Haim, Ilan, Itsik, Menashe, Moshe, Ronen, Tali, Yosef.  French Michel, Yvan, Alain, Armand, Herve, Jacques, Josephe.","Jewish (Sephardic): from the medieval male personal name <i>Viton</i>, from the Romance root <i>vita</i> ‘life’.","English: topographic name perhaps from Middle English <i>bittem</i>, a phonological variant of <i>botme</i> ‘bottom’; compare   Bottom  . Alternatively, a habitational name from a place in Gloucestershire named Bitton. The place takes its name from the Boyd river, a Celtic river name of uncertain origin + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement, farmstead’."]},{"name":"Botham","meanings":["Hebrew: The Lord is upright."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":1,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":46,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":119,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Holl Bottom Graunt was born about 1336, in Burton, Cheshire, England, his father, Thomas Graunt  alias Botton, was 38 and his mother, Scisseley de Bryon, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Gwenlain Tuberville."},"et":{"abt1336–":"umbes 1336–Surnud","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1316–Female":"1316–Surnud","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1455":"1455","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","abt1336":"umbes 1336","1340":"1340","abt 1372":"umbes 1372","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","Dyffryn Golach, Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Burton, Buckingham, England":"Burton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"abt1336–":"noin 1336–Kuollut","1336–Male":"1336–Kuollut","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1372–Male":"1372–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1316–Female":"1316–Kuollut","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1455":"1455","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","abt1336":"noin 1336","1340":"1340","abt 1372":"noin 1372","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","Dyffryn Golach, Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Burton, Buckingham, England":"Burton, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"abt1336–":"environ 1336–Décédé","1336–Male":"1336–Décédé","1340–Female":"1340–Décédée","1372–Male":"1372–Décédé","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1316–F